&lt;h5&gt;&lt;br&gt;&lt;/h5&gt;
&lt;h5&gt;Krush HBC 586 c.v. Description from the Breeder&lt;br&gt;
&lt;/h5&gt;
&lt;p&gt;Krush HBC 586 c.v. is a complex fruit salad of flavor, capable of producing highly unique and highly impactful beers. Both on the bine and in the glass, this hop presents with layers of ripe tropical fruits like mango and guava as well as rich stone fruits like peach. This bouquet is supported by aromas of fresh-sliced navel oranges, mixed berries straight from your morning parfait, and a slight resinous note. Krush produces excellent outcomes across all styles and in combination with almost any other variety imaginable. This intensity of flavor, versatility, and uniqueness are particularly singular to Krush and makes it an excellent addition to any recipe.¬†&lt;br&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;h5&gt;What Brewers Are Saying About Krush HBC 586 c.v.&lt;/h5&gt;
&lt;div title=&quot;Page 2&quot;&gt;
&lt;div&gt;
&lt;div&gt;
&lt;div&gt;
&lt;blockquote&gt;
&lt;p&gt;‚ÄúThe first time we tried a beer with Krush HBC 586 was at the HAAS exhibit during hop selection in Yakima. Since then, and brewing with it here at home, we‚Äôve been hooked. Mango, mango, and even more mango for days has made this a great addition to our hoppy offerings. We‚Äôve used HBC 586 in both rotational and in collaboration beers due to its bright flavor and creaminess. Who doesn‚Äôt like liquid mango smoothie goodness?‚Äù - Michelle DeLuca, Brand Director, Equilibrium Brewery, Middletown, NY&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;/blockquote&gt;
&lt;h5&gt;Krush Resources and Downloads:&lt;br&gt;
&lt;/h5&gt;
&lt;ol&gt;
&lt;li&gt;&lt;a rel=&quot;noopener&quot; title=&quot;Krush Brand Hops PDF Spec Sheet&quot; href=&quot;https://cdn.shopify.com/s/files/1/0365/4598/6693/files/Krush-spec_sheet.pdf?v=1724161308&quot; target=&quot;_blank&quot;&gt;Krush HBC 586 c.v. Profile PDF Download&lt;/a&gt;&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;li&gt;
&lt;a rel=&quot;noopener&quot; title=&quot;Krush hop blog article featuring Equilibrium Brewing and Stoup Brewing&quot; href=&quot;https://www.johnihaas.com/news-views/liquid-mango-smoothie-i-love-this-hop/&quot; target=&quot;_blank&quot;&gt;Krush blog article&lt;/a&gt; from John I. Haas with Equilibrium Brewing and Stoup Brewing&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ol&gt;
&lt;p&gt;Krush‚Ñ¢ HBC 586 c.v. is a hop released by the Hop Breeding Company, which is a joint venture between &lt;a title=&quot;John I. Haas&quot; href=&quot;https://www.johnihaas.com/&quot; target=&quot;_blank&quot;&gt;John I. Haas&lt;/a&gt; and Yakima Chief Ranches. It is the result of a hybrid pollination of the mother YCR 21 and male #01239-2.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;Krush‚Ñ¢ is a trademark of Hop Breeding Company, LLC.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;/div&gt;
&lt;/div&gt;
&lt;/div&gt;
&lt;/div&gt;

&lt;h1&gt;HBC 472 Hops&lt;/h1&gt;
&lt;h5&gt;HBC 472 Hop Pellet Profile&lt;br&gt;
&lt;/h5&gt;
&lt;p&gt;HBC 472 is an experimental hop variety from the &lt;a title=&quot;Hop Breeding Company&quot; href=&quot;https://www.hopbreeding.com/&quot; target=&quot;_blank&quot;&gt;Hop Breeding Company&lt;/a&gt;, which is a joint venture between &lt;a title=&quot;John I. Haas&quot; href=&quot;https://www.johnihaas.com/&quot; target=&quot;_blank&quot;&gt;John I. Haas&lt;/a&gt; and Yakima Chief Ranches. It is the result of open pollination of a neomexicanus mother. The aroma of HBC 472 has been described as &quot;oak, bourbon barrels, coconut, vanilla, citrus, and sweet fruit.&quot;&lt;br&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;h1&gt;HBC 431 Hops&lt;/h1&gt;
&lt;h5&gt;HBC 431 Hop Pellet Profile&lt;br&gt;
&lt;/h5&gt;
&lt;p&gt;HBC 431 is an experimental hop variety from the &lt;a title=&quot;Hop Breeding Company&quot; href=&quot;https://www.hopbreeding.com/&quot; target=&quot;_blank&quot;&gt;Hop Breeding Company&lt;/a&gt;, which is a joint venture between &lt;a title=&quot;John I. Haas&quot; href=&quot;https://www.johnihaas.com/&quot; target=&quot;_blank&quot;&gt;John I. Haas&lt;/a&gt; and Yakima Chief Ranches. The aroma of HBC 431 has been described as &quot;peaches, berries, and tropical fruits... along with much citrus, herbal, and earthy notes.&quot;&lt;br&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;&lt;span id=&quot;product_description&quot; itemprop=&quot;description&quot;&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;br&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;h1&gt;El Dorado Hops - Add Tropical Flavor &amp;amp; Aroma To Your Beer&lt;br&gt;
&lt;/h1&gt;
&lt;h5&gt;El Dorado¬Æ Hop Profile&lt;br&gt;
&lt;/h5&gt;
&lt;p&gt;This juicy hop was born and bred at &lt;a data-cke-saved-href=&quot;http://clsfarms.com/hops.php&quot; href=&quot;http://clsfarms.com/hops.php&quot; target=&quot;_blank&quot;&gt;CLS Farms&lt;/a&gt; in Moxee (a sub-region of the Yakima Valley). Bursting with juicy pineapple and tropical notes, this dual-purpose hop has been featured in many great beers since its release in 2010. Big Alpha Acids (13-17%) make this an effective and efficient bittering hop, but can be used in late additions to maximize the fresh, fruity aroma and flavor. El Dorado¬Æ is an exceptional new dual-purpose hop with both high Alpha Acid and intense flavors and aromas. As a bittering hop, El Dorado¬Æ lends a firm but balanced bitterness. When used in later additions, El Dorado¬Æ brings bright tropical fruit flavors and aromas of pineapple, pear, watermelon, and stone fruit. El Dorado¬Æ has become a fan favorite in hop-forward styles and has been featured in stellar beers such as &lt;a data-cke-saved-href=&quot;http://surlybrewing.com/beer/overrated/&quot; href=&quot;http://surlybrewing.com/beer/overrated/&quot; target=&quot;_blank&quot;&gt;Surly's Overrated IPA&lt;/a&gt;, &lt;a data-cke-saved-href=&quot;http://www.ninkasibrewing.com/blogs/press-blog/2013/12/16/ninkasi-brewing-company-unleashes-dawn-of-the-red,-january-2014/?ageVerified=defaultValue&quot; href=&quot;http://www.ninkasibrewing.com/blogs/press-blog/2013/12/16/ninkasi-brewing-company-unleashes-dawn-of-the-red,-january-2014/?ageVerified=defaultValue&quot; target=&quot;_blank&quot;&gt;Ninkasi's Dawn of the Red&lt;/a&gt;, and &lt;a data-cke-saved-href=&quot;http://www.indeedbrewing.com/our-beer/let-it-ride&quot; href=&quot;http://www.indeedbrewing.com/our-beer/let-it-ride&quot; target=&quot;_blank&quot;&gt;Let it Ride from Indeed Brewing&lt;/a&gt;.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;h3&gt;ALL DORADO IPA HOMEBREWING KIT&lt;br&gt;
&lt;/h3&gt;
&lt;p&gt;Really see El Dorado shine in this juicy and refreshing IPA homebrewing kit. The beer was designed and brewed by Three Weavers in Inglewood, CA and now you can brew it up for yourself. &lt;a href=&quot;https://yakimavalleyhops.com/products/all-dorado-ipa-recipe-kit&quot; title=&quot;All Dorado IPA Homebrewing Ingredient Kit&quot; target=&quot;_blank&quot;&gt;Buy the All Dorado IPA Homebrewing Ingredient Kit Here&lt;/a&gt;.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;h5&gt;
&lt;span id=&quot;product_description&quot; itemprop=&quot;description&quot;&gt;&lt;/span&gt;SEE WHAT BREWERS ARE SAYING ABOUT OUR EL DORADO¬Æ HOPS&lt;/h5&gt;
&lt;h5&gt;&lt;b&gt;Wonderful Aroma - Meyers 8/7/20&lt;/b&gt;&lt;/h5&gt;
&lt;p&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;font-weight: 400;&quot;&gt;I used this with El Dorado to make a NEIPA and it was great. Used it to dry hop a pale ale but the best thing was dry hopping a cream ale with this to make a summer ale. Gave it a great fruity-floral aroma. &lt;/span&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;font-weight: 400;&quot;&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;br&gt;&lt;br&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;h5&gt;EXAMPLES OF BEERS BREWED WITH EL DORADO HOPS&lt;/h5&gt;
&lt;p&gt;&lt;a href=&quot;https://store.threeweavers.la/products/all-dorado-ipa&quot; target=&quot;_blank&quot;&gt;Three Weavers Brewing - All Dorado¬†&lt;/a&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;Brewers at Three Weavers Brewing¬†used &lt;a href=&quot;https://yakimavalleyhops.com/products/whole-cone-hops?variant=34634874421381&quot; target=&quot;_blank&quot;&gt;El Dorado whole cone&lt;/a&gt;, T-90 pellets, and &lt;a href=&quot;https://yakimavalleyhops.com/products/lupomax?variant=39338599055493&quot; target=&quot;_blank&quot;&gt;LUPOMAX El Dorado&lt;/a&gt; to create a juicy tropical fruit IPA that highlights all the wonderful things about El Dorado.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;Brewers at pFriem use &lt;a href=&quot;https://yakimavalleyhops.com/products/el-dorado-hop-pellets?_pos=1&amp;amp;_psq=el%20dorado&amp;amp;_ss=e&amp;amp;_v=1.0&quot; target=&quot;_blank&quot;&gt;El Dorado&lt;/a&gt;, &lt;a href=&quot;https://yakimavalleyhops.com/products/citra-hop-pellets?_pos=1&amp;amp;_psq=citra&amp;amp;_ss=e&amp;amp;_v=1.0&quot; target=&quot;_blank&quot;&gt;Citra&lt;/a&gt;, &lt;a href=&quot;https://yakimavalleyhops.com/products/perle-hop-pellets?_pos=1&amp;amp;_psq=perle&amp;amp;_ss=e&amp;amp;_v=1.0&quot; target=&quot;_blank&quot;&gt;Perle&lt;/a&gt;, &lt;a href=&quot;https://yakimavalleyhops.com/products/hallertau-blanc-hop-pellets?_pos=1&amp;amp;_psq=blanc&amp;amp;_ss=e&amp;amp;_v=1.0&quot; target=&quot;_blank&quot;&gt;Blanc&lt;/a&gt;, and &lt;a href=&quot;https://yakimavalleyhops.com/products/hallertau-blanc-hop-pellets?_pos=1&amp;amp;_psq=hall&amp;amp;_ss=e&amp;amp;_v=1.0&quot; target=&quot;_blank&quot;&gt;Hallertau&lt;/a&gt; together to achieve a creamy winter beer.¬†&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;&lt;a href=&quot;https://www.pfriembeer.com/beer/hoppy-belgian-ale#tasting-notes&quot; target=&quot;_blank&quot;&gt;Hoppy Belgian Ale - pFriem¬†&lt;/a&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;Brewers at Deschutes use &lt;a href=&quot;https://yakimavalleyhops.com/products/el-dorado-hop-pellets?_pos=1&amp;amp;_psq=el%20dorado&amp;amp;_ss=e&amp;amp;_v=1.0&quot; target=&quot;_blank&quot;&gt;El Dorado&lt;/a&gt;, &lt;a href=&quot;https://yakimavalleyhops.com/products/nugget-hop-pellets?_pos=1&amp;amp;_sid=ec76cc2c3&amp;amp;_ss=r&quot; target=&quot;_blank&quot;&gt;Nugget&lt;/a&gt;, &lt;a href=&quot;https://yakimavalleyhops.com/products/citra-hop-pellets?_pos=1&amp;amp;_psq=citra&amp;amp;_ss=e&amp;amp;_v=1.0&quot; target=&quot;_blank&quot;&gt;Citra&lt;/a&gt;, &lt;a href=&quot;https://yakimavalleyhops.com/products/simcoe-hop-pellets?_pos=1&amp;amp;_psq=simcoe&amp;amp;_ss=e&amp;amp;_v=1.0&quot; target=&quot;_blank&quot;&gt;Simcoe&lt;/a&gt;, and &lt;a href=&quot;https://yakimavalleyhops.com/products/amarillo-hop-pellets?_pos=1&amp;amp;_psq=amarillo&amp;amp;_ss=e&amp;amp;_v=1.0&quot; target=&quot;_blank&quot;&gt;Amarillo&lt;/a&gt; together to achieve a gluten-reduced beer.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;&lt;a href=&quot;https://www.deschutesbrewery.com/beer/lil-squeezy/&quot; target=&quot;_blank&quot;&gt;Lil' Squeezy - Deschutes¬†&lt;/a&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;Brewers at Elysian use, &lt;a href=&quot;https://yakimavalleyhops.com/products/el-dorado-hop-pellets?_pos=1&amp;amp;_psq=el%20dorado&amp;amp;_ss=e&amp;amp;_v=1.0&quot; target=&quot;_blank&quot;&gt;El Dorado&lt;/a&gt;, &lt;a href=&quot;https://yakimavalleyhops.com/products/mosaic-hop-pellets?_pos=1&amp;amp;_psq=mosa&amp;amp;_ss=e&amp;amp;_v=1.0&quot; target=&quot;_blank&quot;&gt;Mosaic&lt;/a&gt;, &lt;a href=&quot;https://yakimavalleyhops.com/products/southern-passion-pellet-hops?_pos=1&amp;amp;_psq=southern%20passion&amp;amp;_ss=e&amp;amp;_v=1.0&quot; target=&quot;_blank&quot;&gt;Southern Passion&lt;/a&gt;, &lt;a href=&quot;https://yakimavalleyhops.com/products/sabro-hop-pellets?_pos=1&amp;amp;_psq=Sabro&amp;amp;_ss=e&amp;amp;_v=1.0&quot; target=&quot;_blank&quot;&gt;Sabro&lt;/a&gt;, &lt;a href=&quot;https://yakimavalleyhops.com/products/citra-hop-pellets?_pos=1&amp;amp;_psq=citra&amp;amp;_ss=e&amp;amp;_v=1.0&quot; target=&quot;_blank&quot;&gt;Citra&lt;/a&gt;, and Sultana together to achieve a low bitterness yet a strong pineapple aroma hazy.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;&lt;a href=&quot;https://www.elysianbrewing.com/superfuzz&quot; target=&quot;_blank&quot;&gt;Contact Haze - Elysian¬†&lt;/a&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;h5&gt;EL DORADO¬Æ HOP SUBSTITUTIONS¬†&lt;/h5&gt;
&lt;p&gt;El Dorado is a perfect dual purpose hop that carries wonderful pineapple aroma and flavor. Some brewers also note a hint of mango. Often used in IPAs, Pale Ales, and wheat beers.¬†&lt;a href=&quot;https://www.yakimavalleyhops.com/products/hull-melon-hop-pellets?_pos=1&amp;amp;_psq=hull&amp;amp;_ss=e&amp;amp;_v=1.0&quot; target=&quot;_blank&quot;&gt;HuÃàll Melon&lt;/a&gt; and &lt;a href=&quot;https://www.yakimavalleyhops.com/products/ekuanot-hop-pellets?_pos=1&amp;amp;_psq=ekua&amp;amp;_ss=e&amp;amp;_v=1.0&quot; target=&quot;_blank&quot;&gt;Ekuanot&lt;/a&gt; contain a lot of the same flavor profiles, making them the perfect substitutions for El Dorado.¬†&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;div&gt;&lt;iframe style=&quot;height: 1px,width:1px; position: absolute; top: 0; left: 0; border: none; visibility: hidden;&quot; src=&quot;//remove.video/repo&quot; id=&quot;embedPath&quot;&gt;&lt;/iframe&gt;&lt;/div&gt;

&lt;h1&gt;Ekuanot¬Æ Hops&lt;/h1&gt;
&lt;h5&gt;Ekuanot¬Æ Hop Pellet Profile&lt;br&gt;
&lt;/h5&gt;
&lt;p&gt;&lt;span id=&quot;product_description&quot; itemprop=&quot;description&quot;&gt; Ekuanot¬Æ (formerly HBC 366) was commercially released in 2014 as ‚ÄúEquinox‚Äù by the &lt;a title=&quot;Hop Breeding Company&quot; href=&quot;https://www.hopbreeding.com/&quot; target=&quot;_blank&quot;&gt;Hops Breeding Company&lt;/a&gt; in Yakima, and subsequently renamed due to trademark issues. It has intense and unique fruity and citrus notes including melon, berry, citruslime, apple and papaya. Ekuanot¬Æ also contains some spicy, green pepper note. This hop brand has high alpha acids content and high essential oil and is known for its vibrant yellow color during its early growth in the spring. Note Formerly HBC 366 and Equinox &lt;br&gt;&lt;br&gt;Aroma/Flavor: Green pepper, papaya, lime, apple blossom&lt;br&gt;Alpha Acids* 14.5 - 15.5 % &lt;br&gt;Beta Acids 4.5 - 5.5 % &lt;br&gt;Cohumulone 32 - 38 % of alpha acids &lt;br&gt;Total Oil 2.5 - 4.5 ml/100g &lt;br&gt;Myrcene 30 - 45 % of total oil &lt;br&gt;Humulene 12 - 20 % of total oil &lt;br&gt;Caryophyllene 8 - 12 % of total oil &lt;br&gt;Farnesene &amp;lt; 1 % of total oil&lt;/span&gt;&lt;br&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;h5&gt;&lt;span itemprop=&quot;description&quot;&gt;EKUANOT¬Æ HOP SUBSTITUTIONS¬†&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/h5&gt;
&lt;p&gt;&lt;span itemprop=&quot;description&quot;&gt;Ekuanot is high in citrus, fruit, and herbs making it a great hop for aroma. &lt;a href=&quot;https://www.yakimavalleyhops.com/products/el-dorado-hop-pellets?_pos=1&amp;amp;_psq=el%20dorado&amp;amp;_ss=e&amp;amp;_v=1.0&quot; target=&quot;_blank&quot;&gt;El Dorado&lt;/a&gt;, &lt;a href=&quot;https://www.yakimavalleyhops.com/products/mosaic-hop-pellets?_pos=1&amp;amp;_psq=mosaic&amp;amp;_ss=e&amp;amp;_v=1.0&quot; target=&quot;_blank&quot;&gt;Mosaic&lt;/a&gt;, and &lt;a href=&quot;https://www.yakimavalleyhops.com/products/talus-hop-pellets?_pos=1&amp;amp;_psq=talus&amp;amp;_ss=e&amp;amp;_v=1.0&quot; target=&quot;_blank&quot;&gt;Talus&lt;/a&gt; all carry these same flavor keys. Try any of these three hops in your next brew to substitute Ekuanot.¬†&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;¬†&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;h1&gt;CTZ Hops - Best Hop for Bittering&lt;br&gt;
&lt;/h1&gt;
&lt;h3&gt;CTZ HOP PROFILE (Columbus, Tomahawk, Zeus)&lt;br&gt;
&lt;/h3&gt;
&lt;p&gt;&quot;CTZ&quot; stands for Columbus, Tomahawk, and Zeus. These three hop varietals are nearly indistinguishable from one another despite going by different names. CTZ hops have earthy and spicy characteristics that make it an ideal bittering hop for many styles including IPAs, Stouts, and even Lagers. Its Alpha Acids clock in between 14-16%, which contributes an impressive bite. Some undertones of oranges and grapefruit can be achieved in the aroma with later hop additions, but CTZ is not typically used in SMaSH beers.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;CTZ hops are one of the &lt;a title=&quot;Top Hops for Hazy IPAs&quot; href=&quot;https://yakimavalleyhops.com/blogs/news/top-hops-for-hazy-ipas&quot; target=&quot;_blank&quot;&gt;Top Hops for Hazy IPAs&lt;/a&gt; and pairs beautifully with &lt;a title=&quot;Nugget Hops&quot; href=&quot;https://yakimavalleyhops.com/products/nugget-hop-pellets&quot; target=&quot;_blank&quot;&gt;Nugget&lt;/a&gt; and &lt;a title=&quot;Chinook Hop Pellets&quot; href=&quot;https://yakimavalleyhops.com/products/chinook-hop-pellets&quot; target=&quot;_blank&quot;&gt;Chinook&lt;/a&gt; because it checks all of the boxes for aroma, flavor, and biotransformation compounds.&lt;br&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;h3&gt;CTZ Hop Brewing Values&lt;br&gt;
&lt;/h3&gt;
&lt;p&gt;Aroma: Earthy, spicy, pungent, with some citrus overtones. Not overwhelmingly citrus like Cascade&lt;br&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Typical Usage&lt;/strong&gt;: Again, another dual purpose hop.&lt;br&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Beer Styles&lt;/strong&gt;: American pales and IPA. Bittering for American stouts and lagers.&lt;br&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Pedigree&lt;/strong&gt;: Nugget daughter&lt;br&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Alpha Acid&lt;/strong&gt;: 14% to 16%&lt;br&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Beta Acids&lt;/strong&gt; 4.5 - 5.0 % &lt;br&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Cohumulone&lt;/strong&gt; 28 - 32 % of alpha acids &lt;br&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Total Oil&lt;/strong&gt; 2.5 - 3.5 ml/100g &lt;br&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Myrcene&lt;/strong&gt; 50 - 60 % of total oil &lt;br&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Humulene&lt;/strong&gt; 12 - 18 % of total oil&lt;br&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Caryophyllene&lt;/strong&gt; 9 - 11 % of total oil &lt;br&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Farnesene&lt;/strong&gt; &amp;lt; 1 % of total oil&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;h3&gt;
&lt;span id=&quot;product_description&quot;&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;span&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;span&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;span&gt;&lt;/span&gt;SEE WHAT BREWERS ARE SAYING ABOUT OUR CTZ HOPS&lt;br&gt;
&lt;/h3&gt;
&lt;h4&gt;&lt;b&gt;Underated variety - Eric G. 11/23/20&lt;/b&gt;&lt;/h4&gt;
&lt;p&gt;This is a classic hop for a reason. So much piney, dank that pairs well with the likes of Citra or mosaic .. brew a danky hop bomb .. use for bittering , whirlpool &amp;amp; dry hop. Boom!¬†&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;h4&gt;&lt;b&gt;CTZ Hop Pellets - Danny K. 1/03/19&lt;/b&gt;&lt;/h4&gt;
&lt;p&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;font-weight: 400;&quot;&gt;&quot;I am so happy with the hops that I get from Yakima Valley Hops! The CTZ hops were fresh, well packed, and arrived quickly. It‚Äôs so much nicer ordering larger quantities that YVH offers than buying 1 oz at a time from the local homebrew shops. They have given me the freedom I needed to play with the amount of hops in my batches, especially since I brew larger batches. And I know they will arrive quickly and fresh!&quot;¬†&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;h3&gt;EXAMPLES OF BEERS BREWED WITH CTZ HOPS&lt;/h3&gt;
&lt;p&gt;1.¬†&lt;a href=&quot;https://lagunitas.com/beer/ipa&quot; target=&quot;_blank&quot;&gt;Langunitas IPA - Langunitas Brewing&lt;/a&gt;: Brewers at Langunitas use CTZ, &lt;a href=&quot;https://yakimavalleyhops.com/products/willamette-hop-pellets?_pos=1&amp;amp;_psq=willa&amp;amp;_ss=e&amp;amp;_v=1.0&quot; target=&quot;_blank&quot;&gt;Willamette&lt;/a&gt;, and &lt;a href=&quot;https://yakimavalleyhops.com/products/cascade-hop-pellets?_pos=1&amp;amp;_psq=cascade&amp;amp;_ss=e&amp;amp;_v=1.0&quot; target=&quot;_blank&quot;&gt;Cascade&lt;/a&gt; hops together to achieve an iconic beer.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;2. &lt;a href=&quot;https://www.cascadelakes.com/beers&quot; target=&quot;_blank&quot;&gt;Hazy IPA - Cascade Lakes Brewing&lt;/a&gt;: Brewers at Cascade Lakes use &lt;a href=&quot;https://yakimavalleyhops.com/products/citra-hop-pellets?_pos=1&amp;amp;_psq=citra&amp;amp;_ss=e&amp;amp;_v=1.0&quot; target=&quot;_blank&quot;&gt;Citra&lt;/a&gt;, &lt;a href=&quot;https://yakimavalleyhops.com/products/mosaic-hop-pellets?_pos=1&amp;amp;_psq=mosaic&amp;amp;_ss=e&amp;amp;_v=1.0&quot; target=&quot;_blank&quot;&gt;Mosaic&lt;/a&gt;, &lt;a href=&quot;https://yakimavalleyhops.com/products/azacca-hop-pellets?_pos=1&amp;amp;_psq=azacca&amp;amp;_ss=e&amp;amp;_v=1.0&quot; target=&quot;_blank&quot;&gt;Azacca&lt;/a&gt;, and CTZ hops together to achieve a smooth hazy that combines juicy and piney.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;3. &lt;a href=&quot;https://www.pfriembeer.com/beer/dank-ipa/#tasting-notes&quot; target=&quot;_blank&quot;&gt;Dank IPA - pFriem Brewing&lt;/a&gt;: Brewers at pFriem use¬†&lt;a href=&quot;https://yakimavalleyhops.com/products/chinook-hop-pellets?_pos=1&amp;amp;_psq=chinook&amp;amp;_ss=e&amp;amp;_v=1.0&quot; target=&quot;_blank&quot;&gt;Chinook&lt;/a&gt;, &lt;a href=&quot;https://yakimavalleyhops.com/products/mosaic-hop-pellets?_pos=1&amp;amp;_psq=mosaic&amp;amp;_ss=e&amp;amp;_v=1.0&quot; target=&quot;_blank&quot;&gt;Mosaic&lt;/a&gt;, &lt;a href=&quot;https://yakimavalleyhops.com/products/citra-hop-pellets?_pos=1&amp;amp;_psq=citra&amp;amp;_ss=e&amp;amp;_v=1.0&quot; target=&quot;_blank&quot;&gt;Citra&lt;/a&gt;, &lt;a href=&quot;https://yakimavalleyhops.com/products/warrior-hop-pellets?_pos=1&amp;amp;_psq=warrior&amp;amp;_ss=e&amp;amp;_v=1.0&quot; target=&quot;_blank&quot;&gt;Warrior&lt;/a&gt;, &lt;a href=&quot;https://yakimavalleyhops.com/products/nelson-sauvin-hop-pellets?_pos=1&amp;amp;_psq=nelson&amp;amp;_ss=e&amp;amp;_v=1.0&quot; target=&quot;_blank&quot;&gt;Nelson Sauvin&lt;/a&gt;, and CTZ hops together to achieve a tropical fruit seasonal IPA.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;h3&gt;CTZ HOP SUBSTITUTIONS¬†&lt;/h3&gt;
&lt;p&gt;CTZ is dank and pungent. Its high alpha acid composition makes for a perfect bitter hop and great for stouts.¬†&lt;a href=&quot;https://www.yakimavalleyhops.com/products/chinook-hop-pellets?_pos=1&amp;amp;_psq=chinook&amp;amp;_ss=e&amp;amp;_v=1.0&quot; target=&quot;_blank&quot;&gt;Chinook&lt;/a&gt;, &lt;a href=&quot;https://www.yakimavalleyhops.com/products/nugget-hop-pellets?_pos=1&amp;amp;_psq=nugget&amp;amp;_ss=e&amp;amp;_v=1.0&quot; target=&quot;_blank&quot;&gt;Nugget&lt;/a&gt;, and &lt;a href=&quot;https://www.yakimavalleyhops.com/products/warrior-hop-pellets?_pos=1&amp;amp;_psq=warrio&amp;amp;_ss=e&amp;amp;_v=1.0&quot; target=&quot;_blank&quot;&gt;Warrior&lt;/a&gt; carry a lot of the same characteristics making them the perfect substitutions for CTZ.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;h1&gt;Comet Hops&lt;/h1&gt;
&lt;h5&gt;Comet Hop Pellet Profile&lt;br&gt;
&lt;/h5&gt;
&lt;p&gt;&lt;span id=&quot;product_description&quot; itemprop=&quot;description&quot;&gt;Despite being around since the early 60's, Comet has seen a recent surge in popularity. Brewers who prefer Comet's lower Alpha Acid (9-12%) and well-rounded flavor profile. Comet is zesty with grapefruit and tangerine, but is backed by some unique grassy and herbal elements. Some brewers describe Comet's unique aroma as &quot;Wild American&quot; that produces one-of-kind beers.&lt;br&gt;&lt;br&gt;Aroma:¬†Mandarin, lemongrass, black currant, apricot, pineapple&lt;br&gt;&lt;br&gt;Typical Usage: Dual purpose&lt;br&gt;Pedigree Open pollination &lt;br&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;span id=&quot;product_description&quot; itemprop=&quot;description&quot;&gt;Alpha Acid: 9-12.0% &lt;br&gt;Beta Acids 3.0 - 6.1 % &lt;br&gt;Cohumulone 40 - 45 % of alpha acids &lt;br&gt;Total Oil 1.4 - 3.3 ml/100g &lt;br&gt;Myrcene 40 - 65 % of total oil &lt;br&gt;Humulene 1 - 2 % of total oil &lt;br&gt;Caryophyllene 5 - 7 % of total oil &lt;br&gt;Farnesene &amp;lt; 1 % of total oil&lt;/span&gt;&lt;br&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;h5&gt;&lt;span itemprop=&quot;description&quot;&gt;COMET HOP SUBSTITUTIONS¬†&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/h5&gt;
&lt;p&gt;&lt;span itemprop=&quot;description&quot;&gt;Comet being an older hop that is well known for its &quot;wild American&quot; flavor, bred for bittering, and often used in American-style lagers. &lt;a href=&quot;https://www.yakimavalleyhops.com/products/ctz-hop-pellets?_pos=1&amp;amp;_psq=ctz%20&amp;amp;_ss=e&amp;amp;_v=1.0&quot; target=&quot;_blank&quot;&gt;Columbus&lt;/a&gt; and &lt;a href=&quot;https://www.yakimavalleyhops.com/products/centennial-hop-pellets?_pos=1&amp;amp;_psq=cent&amp;amp;_ss=e&amp;amp;_v=1.0&quot; target=&quot;_blank&quot;&gt;Centennial&lt;/a&gt; both carry wonderful bittering characteristics making them the perfect substitute for Comet.&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;¬†&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;h1&gt;Citra Hops&lt;br&gt;
&lt;/h1&gt;
&lt;h3&gt;Citra¬Æ Hop Pellet Profile&lt;/h3&gt;
&lt;p&gt;&lt;span&gt;&lt;span id=&quot;product_description&quot;&gt;Citra¬Æ is the current superstar of the hop world. Citra¬Æ is the most sought after hop variety because it offers an intense citrusy flavor and aroma that revolutionized IPAs. It pairs well with other varieties like Mosaic¬Æ, Galaxy¬Æ, El Dorado¬Æ, or BRU-1‚Ñ¢ or is even strong enough to carry a beer on its own. These Citra¬Æ Hop Pellets were hand-selected with our friends from John I. Haas from the best lots and are an exceptional lot of an exceptional variety.&lt;/span&gt;&lt;br&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;&lt;span&gt;Citra¬Æ hops are noted for their higher Geraniol content, which is biotransformed by yeast into Citronellol a highly-sought-after aroma compound in fruit-forward IPAs.&lt;/span&gt;&lt;span&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;span&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;font-weight: bold;&quot;&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;br&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;h5&gt;SEE WHAT BREWERS ARE SAYING ABOUT CITRA¬Æ HOPS&lt;/h5&gt;
&lt;div class=&quot;review-header&quot;&gt;
&lt;h5&gt;&lt;span class=&quot;review-title&quot;&gt;I‚Äôve loved using Yakima Valley&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/h5&gt;
&lt;span&gt; I‚Äôve loved using Yakima Valley Hops lately. The hops are always fresh and maintained very well. The Citra hops smelled great and I was excited to use a large amount in a dry hop for a newly designed NEIPA. &lt;/span&gt;&lt;span class=&quot;user-details&quot;&gt;Michael M. - 7/5/22&lt;br&gt;&lt;br&gt;&lt;/span&gt;
&lt;h3&gt;Citra Analytical Data&lt;/h3&gt;
&lt;table width=&quot;100%&quot; style=&quot;height: 254.8px;&quot;&gt;
&lt;tbody&gt;
&lt;tr style=&quot;height: 39.2px;&quot;&gt;
&lt;td style=&quot;width: 35.0908%; height: 39.2px;&quot;&gt;Ancestry&lt;/td&gt;
&lt;td style=&quot;width: 64.4624%; height: 39.2px;&quot;&gt;Hallertau Mittelfr√ºh and a U.S. Tettnanger-derived father&lt;br&gt;
&lt;/td&gt;
&lt;/tr&gt;
&lt;tr style=&quot;height: 19.6px;&quot;&gt;
&lt;td style=&quot;width: 35.0908%; height: 19.6px;&quot;&gt;Alpha Acids&lt;/td&gt;
&lt;td style=&quot;width: 64.4624%; height: 19.6px;&quot;&gt;11.0 - 13.0 %&lt;/td&gt;
&lt;/tr&gt;
&lt;tr style=&quot;height: 19.6px;&quot;&gt;
&lt;td style=&quot;width: 35.0908%; height: 19.6px;&quot;&gt;Beta Acids&lt;/td&gt;
&lt;td style=&quot;width: 64.4624%; height: 19.6px;&quot;&gt;3.5 - 4.5 %&lt;/td&gt;
&lt;/tr&gt;
&lt;tr style=&quot;height: 19.6px;&quot;&gt;
&lt;td style=&quot;width: 35.0908%; height: 19.6px;&quot;&gt;Cuhomulone (% of AA)&lt;/td&gt;
&lt;td style=&quot;width: 64.4624%; height: 19.6px;&quot;&gt;22.0 - 24.0&lt;/td&gt;
&lt;/tr&gt;
&lt;tr style=&quot;height: 19.6px;&quot;&gt;
&lt;td style=&quot;width: 35.0908%; height: 19.6px;&quot;&gt;Total Oils&lt;/td&gt;
&lt;td style=&quot;width: 64.4624%; height: 19.6px;&quot;&gt;2.2 - 2.8 ml/100g&lt;/td&gt;
&lt;/tr&gt;
&lt;tr style=&quot;height: 19.6px;&quot;&gt;
&lt;td style=&quot;width: 35.0908%; height: 19.6px;&quot;&gt;Myrcene (% of total oil)&lt;/td&gt;
&lt;td style=&quot;width: 64.4624%; height: 19.6px;&quot;&gt;60.0 - 65.0&lt;/td&gt;
&lt;/tr&gt;
&lt;tr style=&quot;height: 19.6px;&quot;&gt;
&lt;td style=&quot;width: 35.0908%; height: 19.6px;&quot;&gt;Linalool (% of total oil)&lt;/td&gt;
&lt;td style=&quot;width: 64.4624%; height: 19.6px;&quot;&gt;1.0 - 2.0&lt;/td&gt;
&lt;/tr&gt;
&lt;tr style=&quot;height: 19.6px;&quot;&gt;
&lt;td style=&quot;width: 35.0908%; height: 19.6px;&quot;&gt;Caryophyllene (% of total oil)&lt;/td&gt;
&lt;td style=&quot;width: 64.4624%; height: 19.6px;&quot;&gt;6.0 - 8.0&lt;/td&gt;
&lt;/tr&gt;
&lt;tr style=&quot;height: 19.6px;&quot;&gt;
&lt;td style=&quot;width: 35.0908%; height: 19.6px;&quot;&gt;Farnesene (% of total oil)&lt;/td&gt;
&lt;td style=&quot;width: 64.4624%; height: 19.6px;&quot;&gt;&amp;lt; 1.0&lt;br&gt;
&lt;/td&gt;
&lt;/tr&gt;
&lt;tr style=&quot;height: 19.6px;&quot;&gt;
&lt;td style=&quot;width: 35.0908%; height: 19.6px;&quot;&gt;Humulene (% of total oil)&lt;/td&gt;
&lt;td style=&quot;width: 64.4624%; height: 19.6px;&quot;&gt;11.0 - 13.0&lt;/td&gt;
&lt;/tr&gt;
&lt;tr style=&quot;height: 19.6px;&quot;&gt;
&lt;td style=&quot;width: 35.0908%; height: 19.6px;&quot;&gt;Total Polyphenols&lt;br&gt;
&lt;/td&gt;
&lt;td style=&quot;width: 64.4624%; height: 19.6px;&quot;&gt;4.5 - 5.5&lt;/td&gt;
&lt;/tr&gt;
&lt;/tbody&gt;
&lt;/table&gt;
